This paper presents a data structure for dynamic connectivity in undirected graphs, which is a fundamental problem in computer science. The paper focuses on worst-case deterministic algorithms, which suggests that it belongs to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) category. The algorithm's performance is analyzed using techniques from combinatorics and graph theory, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) category. The problem of dynamic connectivity is closely related to computational geometry, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) category. The paper also mentions previous work on dynamic connectivity, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) category. Finally, the paper presents an algorithm with improved worst-case performance, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.AL (Algorithms) category.
